<p>This stopped my heart:</p>

<p>â€œ(Iâ€™ve heard it said that Daisyâ€™s murmur was only to make people lean toward her; an irrelevant criticism that made it no less charming.)â€</p>

<p>The best sentences evoke sensations, and this one evokes three: sound, sight and kinesthesia. I hear Daisy murmur, I see people leaning in, and I feel the bend in my own body, as I try to catch Daisyâ€™s words.</p>

<p>With great economy, the sentence informs me she is a habitual murmurer. I know that indirectly, deducing it from the fact that she murmurs so often that people gossip about it. From the sentence, I also learn that Daisy has detractors.Â </p>

<p>And I learn that Nick, the narrator, is quick to defend her. Itâ€™s a fascinating effect, because by defending her, he undermines her. Iâ€™d have no way of knowing that people distrust her if he didnâ€™t tell us their skepticism is irrelevant. (Imagine a â€œfriendâ€ saying, â€œIt doesnâ€™t matter what anyones says. I will always think youâ€™re attractive!â€) He sounds defensive, which shines a spotlight on the criticism. Iâ€™m suddenly sure that Daisy is manipulative. And Iâ€™m sure Nick is too smitten to know her true nature. Which has the effect of undermining him as a narrator. Heâ€™s proven himself to be biased, not objective.Â </p>

<p>I also believe Daisy, though deceitful,Â 
is
