In her story â€œThe Blood Jet,â€ Schutt ends a sentence about â€œlife after a certain ageâ€ by describing it capsularly as â€œacutely felt, clearly flatâ€â€”two pairs of words in which an adverb precedes an adjective. The adjectives (feltÂ andÂ flat) are both monosyllabic, they are both four letters in length, and they both share the same consonantal casing: they begin with a tentative-sounding, deflatingÂ fÂ and end with the abruptÂ t.Â In between the two ends of each adjective, Schutt retains theÂ l,Â though it slides one space backward in the second adjective; and for the interior vowel, she moves downward from a shortÂ eÂ to a shortÂ a.Â The predecessive adverbsÂ acutelyÂ andÂ clearlyÂ share theÂ k-soundingÂ c,Â and both words are constituted of virtually the same letters, except thatclearlyÂ doesnâ€™t retain theÂ tÂ ofÂ acutely.Â The four-word phrase has a resigned and final sound to it; there is more than a little agony in how, with just two little adjustments,Â feltÂ has been diminished and transmogrified intoÂ flat,Â in how the richness of receptivity summed up inÂ feltÂ has been leveled into the thudding spiritlessness ofÂ flat.Â All of this emotion has been delivered by the most ordinary of wordsâ€”nothing dredged up from a thesaurus. But what is perhaps most striking about the four-word phrase is the family resemblances between the two pairs of words. There is nothing in the letter-by-letter makeup of the phrase â€œclearly flatâ€ that wasnâ€™t already physically present in â€œacutely feltâ€; the second of the two phrases contains the alphabetic DNA of the first phrase. There isnâ€™t, of course, an exact, anagrammatic correspondence between the two pairs of words; theÂ uÂ of the first pair, after all, hasnâ€™t been carried over into the second pair. (Schutt isnâ€™t stooping to recreational word games here.) But the page-hugging, rather than page-turning, readerâ€”the very reader whom a writer such as Schutt enthrallsâ€”cannot help noticing that the second 