Gordon Lishâ€”the enormously influential editor, writer, and teacher whom I mentioned earlierâ€”instructed his students in a poetics of the sentence that emphasized what he called consecution: a recursive procedure by which one word pursues itself into its successor by discharging something from deep within itself into what follows. The discharge can take many forms and often produces startling outcomes, such as when Christine Schutt, in â€œThe Summer after Barbara Claffey,â€ is seeking the inevitable adjective to insert into the final slot in the sentence â€œHere is the house at night, lit up tall and <strong>__</strong>.â€ What she winds up doing is literally dragging forward the previous adjective,Â tall,Â and using it as the base on which further letters can be erected. The result is the astounding, perfecttallowyâ€”the sort of adjective she never could have arrived at if she had turned a synonymicon upside down in search of words that capture the quality of light.
