<p>Passivity</p>

<p>In 90% of cases, the worst kind of sentence or phrase is the passive one. Iâ€™m referring to both the grammatical passive-voice and to any phrase which doesnâ€™t indicate who is doing what to whom.</p>

<p>Example: â€œMistakes were made.â€</p>

<p>Some passive sentences do contain all the information needed to understand who is doing what to whom, but words are in a funky order:</p>

<p>Example: â€œMistakes were made by John.â€</p>

<p>Itâ€™s almost seems as if John took no part in the mistakes he made. As if â€œmaking mistakesâ€ just happened to him.</p>

<p>Though they have their uses, sentences like these usually lack clear imagery and avoid social reasoning (Who made the mistakes?). Worse, they often cloak dishonesty (â€œIâ€™d rather not say who made the mistakesâ€) or muddle-headedness (â€œI donâ€™t know who made the mistakes.â€)</p>

<p>Here are some possible fixes:</p>

<p>â€œJohn screwed up.â€</p>

<p>â€œThe Planning Committee bungled the whole affair.â€</p>

<p>(A passive version of the above is â€œThe whole affair was bungled by the Planning Committee.â€ Compare that to the active version and notice that itâ€™s harder to parse. Our brains tend to want to know who the doer is before we worry about what heâ€™s doing.)</p>

<p>If you take a look at Quora questions, youâ€™ll see many of them expressed with passive phrases:</p>

<p>â€œIs kissing considered too-forward on the first date?â€</p>

<p>Considered by whom?</p>

<p>â€œAre children indoctrinated by Religion?â€</p>

