<p>The writer of the kissing question is probably using passive phrasing because heâ€™s confused. He has a vague idea that â€œitâ€™s not done,â€ but heâ€™s unsure who makes the rules and when they should be followed. The second writer is playing politics. Heâ€™s passive-aggressively accusing theists of indoctrinating children while leaving himself wiggle room to back away if necessary.</p>

<p>(I copped out above, when I wrote â€œyouâ€™ll see many of them expressed with passive phrases.â€ Who is doing all this expressing. Perhaps I meant â€œQuestion writers express themselves with passive sentences,â€ but shied away from openly accusing them. I only caught this mistake when I read my first draft.)</p>

<p>My point here isnâ€™t to judge rhetoricians. Itâ€™s to point out that passive writing tends to be unclear. Itâ€™s not impenetrable. Rather, it blows a vague cloud towards the reader rather than something in sharp focus.</p>

<p>So as you redraft, sniff out passive sentences and ask yourself â€œWho is doing what to whom?â€ If you donâ€™t know, at least consider being honest, writing â€œSome unknown person made mistakesâ€ instead of â€œMistakes were made.â€ Or, if youâ€™d rather wax passive, know that youâ€™re trading clarity for deception. Youâ€™re trying to hide what you donâ€™t know.</p>

